               <w>akalṣälle</w>
               <w>olyapo</w>
               <lb corresp="#a4"/>
               <gap reason="lost"/>
               <w><supplied>ma</supplied>hendrasene</w>
               <w>walo</w>
               <lb corresp="#a5"/>
               <gap reason="lost"/>
               <gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/>
               <w><supplied>ma</supplied>hen<supplied>dr</supplied>asene</w>
               <w>lāṃ<lb corresp="#b1"/><supplied>t</supplied></w>
               <gap reason="lost"/>
               <gap reason="plain" quantity="2"/>
               <w><supplied>perne</supplied>ṣṣe</w>
               <w>akā<lb/><supplied>lksa</supplied></w>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p>
               <note type="remarks">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:broomhead1962"/><citedRange>143</citedRange></bibl>, this is one of three manuscriprs mentioning King Mahendrasena (the other two being <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch1"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch63"/>). He goes on to describe <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch1"/> and this ms. as "five line manuscripts, written in the same large ductus, but probably not following. The state of preservation of both is very clear, but [ <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch1"/> ] has been blackened appreciably, whereas [this ms.] is white." Cf. also ibid: 144: "the right hand edge of a five line manuscript ... The verso has only one line."</note>
            </p>
